{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e4cd71fe-d179-4e1d-b267-a16e6f9a0b4d","content":"Add an `mcp.json` file in your workspace's `.vscode/` folder:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Place at `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root.\n- `\"type\": \"stdio\"` means Copilot communicates via stdin/stdout.\n- `dotnet run --project` builds and launches your server.\n- After saving, VS Code should detect it automatically — you can verify in the Copilot chat panel under the MCP tools icon (🔧).\n\nIf your server uses a specific launch profile or needs environment variables, you can add an `\"env\"` block alongside `\"command\"`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"94ff833d-da51-4640-a921-96a49cdeaba5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure `mcp.json` to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me check if there's an existing project to understand the setup.","outputTokens":290},"id":"5298df0b-b2ee-4560-b524-7faea9f79dbc","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:50:48.340Z","parentId":"8c57caed-f745-4063-a71f-0a3cbd16a4c9"}
